ng> Your website claims that GMOs help reduce pesticide usage, so why are you trying to buy\r\nSyngenta, the largest pesticide producer in the world?\r\n\r\n<strong>HG:</strong> Just in case\r\n\r\n<strong>SK:</strong> What about cross-pollination? How can an organic farmer protect his crops from contamination\r\nfrom a neighboring GM field?\r\n\r\n<strong>HG:</strong> GMOs are safe to eat\r\n\r\n<strong>SK:</strong> Many GMO farmers grow just a few types of plants. Doesn\'t this “mono-cropping” make our food system vulnerable?\r\n\r\n<strong>HG:</strong> Right, but the thing is GMOs are safe to eat.\r\n\r\n<strong>SK:</strong> Do you think if GM foods were labeled in the US your company would lose money?\r\n\r\n<strong>HG:</strong> It\'s not about profits necessarily; our opposition to labeling of GMOs is common sense really. I mean, haven\'t you ever been so proud of something you created that you would go to absolutely any\r\nlengths to conceal it?\r\n\r\n<strong>SK:</strong> umm...\r\n\r\n<strong>HG:</strong> That\'s why I\'m using all the financial and political resources of the greatest biotechnology company on Earth to fight the misinformation & to change the minds of the misguided people who judge our products with skepticism just because we poisoned a few million people in the past.\r\n\r\n<strong>SK:</strong> Wait, what?\r\n\r\n<strong>HG:</strong> Our products are so safe & so healthy for people and the environment that I will label them over my dead body!\r\n','Monsanto CEO: \'GMOs will be labeled over my dead body\'','','inherit','closed','closed','','74-revision-v1','','','2015-11-02 05:36:45','2015-11-02 05:36:45','',74,'http://ec2-54-68-184-179.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com/index.php/2015/11/02/74-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(78,1,'2015-11-02 06:08:16','2015-11-02 06:08:16','WASHINGTON, D.C.—The Grocery Manufacturers Association (GMA) responds to the recent report released by the World Health Organization\'s International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) which classified processed meat as carcinogenic. \r\n\r\nWe noticed several flaws in their analysis. It is clear that many of the observational studies used do not constitute sufficient or appropriate evidence and therefore do not allow us to conclude with full confidence that processed meats are carcinogenic. In fact, it\'s quite the opposite. \r\n\r\nWe felt a multi-year study was needed where the diets of large numbers of individuals were fully controlled. The GMA in collaboration with the National Pork Producers Council conducted a large-scale study where cancer patients were fed nothing but bacon and hot dogs for two years upon diagnosis and they were given no other medical treatment whatsoever. Nearly every participant was in remission by the end of the first year and many of them have reported enjoying the diet so much that they have stuck with their healthy meat-based diets even after the study.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, a second group of healthy participants went on the same diet and were found to become taller, more energetic and generally more attractive within the first six months of the study. Furthermore, there was a statistically significant increase in penis size for male participants. Full report is <a href=\"http://www.peta.org/\">here.</a> \r\n\r\nWhile we don\'t wish to accuse the IARC of any intentional wrongdoing, it should be noted that they have a long history of sucking the joy out of every known avenue of pleasure. It\'s also true that several of the researchers who conducted the analysis are suspected of engaging in blatant veganism, making their results extremely biased.\r\n\r\n--GMA','Grocery Manufacturers Association Claims WHO Study Flawed, Bacon & Hot Dogs Actually Cure Cancer','','inherit','closed','closed','','66-revision-v1','','','2015-11-02 06:08:16','2015-11-02 06:08:16','',66,'http://ec2-54-68-184-179.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com/index.php/2015/11/02/66-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(79,1,'2015-11-02 06:10:25','2015-11-02 06:10:25','WASHINGTON, D.C.—The Grocery Manufacturers Association (GMA) responds to the recent report released by the World Health Organization\'s International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) which classified processed meat as carcinogenic. \r\n\r\n\"We noticed several flaws in their analysis. It is clear that many of the observational studies used do not constitute sufficient or appropriate evidence and therefore do not allow us to conclude with full confidence that processed meats are carcinogenic. In fact, it\'s quite the opposite. \r\n\r\nWe felt a multi-year study was needed where the diets of large numbers of individuals were fully controlled. The GMA in collaboration with the National Pork Producers Council conducted a large-scale study where cancer patients were fed nothing but bacon and hot dogs for two years upon diagnosis and they were given no other medical treatment whatsoever. Nearly every participant was in remission by the end of the first year and many of them have reported enjoying the diet so much that they have stuck with their healthy meat-based diets even after the study.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, a second group of healthy participants went on the same diet and were found to become taller, more energetic and generally more attractive within the first six months of the study. Furthermore, there was a statistically significant increase in penis size for male participants. Full report is <a href=\"http://www.peta.org/\">here.</a> \r\n\r\nWhile we don\'t wish to accuse the IARC of any intentional wrongdoing, it should be noted that they have a long history of sucking the joy out of every known avenue of pleasure. It\'s also true that several of the researchers who conducted the analysis are suspected of engaging in blatant veganism, making their results extremely biased.\"\r\n\r\n--GMA','Grocery Manufacturers Association Claims WHO Study Flawed, Bacon & Hot Dogs Actually Cure Cancer','','inherit','closed','closed','','66-revision-v1','','','2015-11-02 06:10:25','2015-11-02 06:10:25','',66,'http://ec2-54-68-184-179.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com/index.php/2015/11/02/66-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(80,1,'2015-11-02 06:56:02','2015-11-02 06:56:02','WASHINGTON, D.C.—The Grocery Manufacturers Association (GMA) responds to the recent report released by the World Health Organization\'s International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) which classified processed meat as carcinogenic. \r\n\r\n\"We noticed several flaws in their analysis. It is clear that many of the observational studies used do not constitute sufficient or appropriate evidence and therefore do not allow us to conclude with full confidence that processed meats are carcinogenic. In fact, it\'s quite the opposite. \r\n\r\nWe felt a multi-year study was needed where the diets of large numbers of individuals were fully controlled. The GMA in collaboration with the National Pork Producers Council conducted a large-scale study where cancer patients were fed nothing but bacon and hot dogs for two years upon diagnosis and they were given no other medical treatment whatsoever. Nearly every participant was in remission by the end of the first year and many of them have reported enjoying the diet so much that they have stuck with their healthy meat-based diets even after the study.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, a second group of healthy participants went on the same diet and were found to become taller, more energetic and generally more attractive within the first six months of the study. Furthermore, there was a statistically significant increase in penis size for male participants. Full report is <a href=\"http://www.peta.org/\">here.</a> \r\n\r\nWhile we don\'t wish to accuse the IARC of any intentional wrongdoing, it should be noted that they have a long history of sucking the joy out of every known avenue of pleasure. It\'s also true that several of the researchers who conducted the analysis are suspected of engaging in blatant veganism, making their results extremely biased.\"\r\n\r\n--GMA\r\n\r\n\r\n<font size=\"2\">follow <a href=\"https://twitter.com/skennycomedy\">skenny</a> on twitter</font>','Grocery Manufacturers Association Claims WHO Study Flawed, Bacon & Hot Dogs Actually Cure Cancer','','inherit','closed','closed','','66-revision-v1','','','2015-11-02 06:56:02','2015-11-02 06:56:02','',66,'http://ec2-54-68-184-179.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com/index.php/2015/11/02/66-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(81,1,'2015-11-02 06:58:18','2015-11-02 06:58:18','WASHINGTON, D.C.—The Grocery Manufacturers Association (GMA) responds to the recent report released by the World Health Organization\'s International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) which classified processed meat as carcinogenic. \r\n\r\n\"We noticed several flaws in their analysis. It is clear that many of the observational studies used do not constitute sufficient or appropriate evidence and therefore do not allow us to conclude with full confidence that processed meats are carcinogenic. In fact, it\'s quite the opposite. \r\n\r\nWe felt a multi-year study was needed where the diets of large numbers of individuals were fully controlled. The GMA in collaboration with the National Pork Producers Council conducted a large-scale study where cancer patients were fed nothing but bacon and hot dogs for two years upon diagnosis and they were given no other medical treatment whatsoever. Nearly every participant was in remission by the end of the first year and many of them have reported enjoying the diet so much that they have stuck with their healthy meat-based diets even after the study.\r\n\r\nAdditionally, a second group of healthy participants went on the same diet and were found to become taller, more energetic and generally more attractive within the first six months of the study. Furthermore, there was a statistically significant increase in penis size for male participants. Full report is <a href=\"http://www.peta.org/\">here.</a> \r\n\r\nW